column1: Washington State Median Household Income Estimates by County: 1989 to 2022. Preliminary estimates for 2023 and Projections for 2024

1. 1989 and 1999 median income values were derived from the 1989 and 1999 American Housing Survey (AHS). Survey data release dates - October 1, 1999,  October 1, 2000 as the AHS 1989 and 1999 National Public Use Files (PUF)
2. 2010 median income values were derived from the 2010 US Census of Population and Housing  via the American Community Survey (ACS) data, released December 21, 2010.

3. Unless otherwise stated all estimates beginning with the year 2019 come from the U.S. Census Bureau, Small Area Income and Poverty Estimates (SAIPE) Program, Project No. P-7502872 / Approval CBDRB. Data used in SAIPE estimates come from the annual American Community Survey (ACS).
4. Payroll and personal income data from the Washington State Employment Security Department and the Washington Economic and Revenue Council are used to validate projections.

5. Money income, as defined by the Bureau of the Census, includes wage or salary income, self-employment income, interest, dividends, rental income, social security or other public assistance income, retirement, and disability income; etc.
excludes employer-paid pension and medical benefits. The median measures the point at which half of all households have more income and half have less.
